<br>
example 1: Original coh. This spell would <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  completely strip aggro</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> from anyone, at any distance, including yourself. Also had the potential for making time sinks such as clearing trash mobs, or key quests totally moot. Obviously unbalancing and was nerfed.<br>
<br>
example 2: Original mod rod 2. This spell would generate mana. All the mana an entire raid would require could be made 10 mins pre engage by a handful of magicians and clerics. Again, obviously unbalancing and was removed.<br>
<br>
example 3: Anti-summoning shield. So obviously overpowered it never even went in the game.<br>
<br>
I'm sure if they could, they would have considered giving us a summon which makes real time hours increase for friends at the detriment of enemies by now, lol.<br>
<br>
Not once, but <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  3 times</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> mages have been given spells which completely undermine and trivialize universal balancing aspects of the game: aggro and mana. <br>
<br>
We have to ask ourselves <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  why</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. No other class but us has to switch specializations so often. Why does verant consistently give us summons so overpowered, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  balance our class around them</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, only to nerf them? Why us, but not other classes?<br>
<br>
Personally, i feel they do it for a few reasons.<br>
1) You'll find it hard to argue mages are not underpowered when our utility summons are taken away. We've been in this situation in various ways <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  since kunark</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
Most mages would prefer to be damage dealers. However, damage is a sensitive issue since it is so easily quantified in usefulness. Support is not.<br>
<br>
Verant would like to upgrade us, but they don't want to do it at the detriment of other classes (which may cause them to ask for upgrades, encouraging a vicious cycle which wastes precious hours of time and money).<br>
So, verant has consistently opted to upgrade us in utility first, and damage second.<br>
<br>
They don't have to listen to wizards, druids, or any melee/pet class then. A few murmurs from support classes may arise but they will quickly pass since its a hard position to argue.<br>
<br>
2) Mages are a very small player base. For this reason, relatively little thought goes into our spells. What they may at first glance view as &quot;a cool new ability but not overly useful&quot; has hidden potential to break or make the game.<br>
<br>
Has anyone else ever thought about this issue, if so what conclusions have you drawn?<br>
